bug.short_desc: [Commands] DONE notification fired by operation history before transaction is committed in WriteCommand

long_desc.thetext:
The AbstractModelActionDelegate and AbstractModelActionHandler use a composite WriteCommand to allow subclasses to read and write the model. The current implementation of the WriteCommand will close the operation on the history before the write transaction for the operation is committed. This means that clients will receive a DONE notification from the operation history before they receive the EMF events indicating changes to the model. Clients expect the transaction to be committed before receiving the DONE notification from the operation history.
As it stands, the problem isn't too bad because clients will get a second DONE notification when the operation finishes executing, by which time the EMF notifications have been sent.
It would be best if the DONE notification is sent only once, after the transaction has been comitted.
Moving to the next release, GMF 2.1.

bug.short_desc: Problem with breakpoints in source files not found in source containers

bug.short_desc: [j2ee] Web App Libraries should store JavaDoc / Source in the project

This file is located in your eclipse workspace, not your project .settings, and there's no way to change it. Thus, there is no way to check this file into scm for example, so that it must be maintained from machine to machine.

bug.short_desc: Attach local Javadoc archive using a relative path or variable

long_desc.thetext:
When associating Javadoc to a library, there is no way to make a relative association. All associations are either URLs to local or remote resources, or "Javdoc in archive" which also captures an absolute path. "Javadoc in archive" even captures an absolute path when the Javadoc archive is located in the workspace.
This prevents teams from sharing projects files that make reference to Javadoc for 3rd party libs that live within the project's workspace, unless all team members use the same drive/directory layout.
Additionally, there is no way to extend a variable (like one can with source) for Javadoc.
It's desirable is some situations to store the source and Javadoc with the 3rd party libraries within the project. The team can all share the benefits of navigating source and documentation without having to maintain it individually, and without having to actively hit the internet for public documentation.
Regards, Christian

bug.short_desc: [build path] Ease management of attached source and Javadoc

long_desc.thetext:
I regularly experience a few pain-points regarding jar upgrades and associating Javadoc and source.
#1: We name our jars with the version embedded in the name (e.g. spring-2.0, hibernate-3.1.3, etc). Each time we upgrade the jar, the name changes (obviously). If I use the user interface to make the change (project properties > java build path > libraries), I will lose the already associated source and Javadoc values. It's likely they need to change anyway (though not always, especially for Javadoc), but it's a lot quicker to change the value than to set it from scratch since it's often only a single digit. A work-around is to edit the .classpath file directly.
There should be a way to point a library entry to a new file without reseting the Javadoc and source attachments to blank.
Another alternative might be to decide on a convention, that if the user chooses to follow, eclipse can automatically make Javadoc and source associations. One such convention might be to specific a ext-docs and ext-src directory (possible a variable extension), and if zip exists with the same filename as a project jar then eclipse can auto-associate. For example:
some-project/lib/spring-2.0.jar (in the classpath) some-project/ext-src/spring-2.0-src.zip (auto-associated with spring-2.0) some-project/ext-doc/spring-2.0-doc.zip (auto-associated with spring-2.0)
#2: Eclipse assumes that there is a one-to-one association between jar and Javadoc and source. That is, a single jar can be associated with only a single javadoc location or source attachment. I have encountered some situations where a 3rd party library will have its code split into multiple src directories, even though it's code is all contained in a single jar. Spring places code under src and tiger. Thus, there's no way associate all of the source with the spring jar.
There should be a way to handle scenarios like this, though this isn't as big a deal as #1 IMHO
Final thoughts: My team and I find associated doc/source very helpful during development, and we're always trying to find a way to minimize maintenance of this information. Being able to do so would certainly make life easier for teams who use eclipse, especially larger teams.

I updated the 'Edit' on the library page of the build path wizard to not clear the attributes > 20061006 For 2, please file a separate feature request against jdt.core. However, this is very difficult if not impossible to change at this stage.

bug.short_desc: Can not view .ecore_diagram in editor but can view in outline

This is for any GMF diagram, even the default provided examples.

bug.short_desc: Server fails to deploy jars when they aren't in WEB-INF/lib

long_desc.thetext:
I keep my runtime libraries in a directory at the top of my project (e.g. foo/lib), not under WEB-INF/lib (e.g. foo/web/WEB-INF/lib). This makes more sense from a directory structure to me, and is also more standard IMHO.
Eclipse deals with this just fine from a compilation and development standpoint. However, WTP cannot deploy the web application. The jars aren't copied to the deploy directory, and thus, the classes cannot be found.
The special "Web App Libraries" jar 'container' should be smart enough to copy any jars your app depends on, or allow the user to manually specify what jars are required by the web app at runtime. I think I like the second option better, but in the end, all I want it to be able to utilize the WTP server integration to its fullest extent without having to adhere to a somewhat unusual project structure.
Considering that maven is gaining some momentum, and it too uses a different directory structure than WTP expects, this seems to be a noteworthy problem.
Regards, Christian

You can already do this using the J2EE Module Dependancies properties page on the project - when you add a jar it is automatically added to the build path and included in the published contents.
AFAIK you should just be able to use this page and your problem is solved. Moving bug to the correct component in case you have problems or other questions.

You can either add each jar as a module dependency or edit your .component file to add an entry for the foo/lib folder to be mapped to web-inf/lib at runtime. At runtime, all jars for a web project MUST be in the web-inf/lib directory by j2ee spec.

I tested the J2EE Module Dependency solution, and it does the trick.
I didn't see a way to attach source or Javadoc to those dependencies, which is a separate issue altogether. I'll open a ticket for that.
I still feel that managing libraries in a web app is somewhat obtuse. Libraries are specified in a number of different places in the UI, and captured in very different places on the file system.
Thanks, Christian

bug.short_desc: get adviceDidNotMatch warning as well as "advises" for piece of advice in project on aspectpath
